The goal of this project was to develop a new framework where teams of mobile robots self-engineer the structure of their communication network in order to improve on the performance of distributed algorithms used for collaborative sensing and team coordination. The major outcomes of this project include:

1) Distributed methods for the design of stationary or mobile networks so that distributed coordination and information propagation algorithms implemented over these networks converge fast;

2) Fast distributed algorithms for optimal routing and rate control of mobile robot networks operating in complex environments;

3) Distributed intermittent connectivity control methods that allow robots to temporarily disconnect from the network in order to accomplish tasks more efficiently, free of communication constraints;

4) High-level task planning and communication control methods for networks of robots that live in uncertain and unknown environments; and

5) Distributed methods for optimal area coverage and state estimation using mobile sensor networks, subject to constraints that ensure reliable end-to-end communication with a fixed infrastructure;

6) Risk-averse methods for planning the motion of mobile sensor networks in order to maximize the information they collect in uncertain and unknown environments.

Ultimately, this research has developed a new framework where mobile robot networks are controlled jointly in the space of network configurations and robot positions. The study of these integrated systems has required the synthesis of new theoretical results drawing from control theory, spectral graph theory, wireless networking, and optimization.

